This one was around off, on a length. Kohli prods to defend but gets a thick outside edge through the slip cordon. The fielder chases it back, dives and does well to save a single for his team.
BEATEN! A length ball, outside off, it and shapes away. Kohli looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Touch short, on off. Kohli gets on the front foot and blocks it on the off side.
Short in length, on off. Kohli solidly blocks it on the surface.
Shorter and on off. Kohli defends it to point.
On a length, on off. Kept out.
A short ball, outside leg, Ravindra Jadeja just takes his eyes off the ball and takes it on his left shoulder. Does not show any pain but that would have stung.
Another full ball, slanting across, outside off. Left alone.
Again a full ball, outside off. Jadeja leaves it alone.
Hurls a full ball, shaping away from the left-hander, outside off. Left alone.
A full ball, angling across, outside off. Jadeja lets it through.
Again serves a full ball, on off. Kohli gets on the front foot and pushes it to covers.
A full ball, outside off. Kohli pushes it to covers.
A length ball, outside off. Kohli shoulders arms to it.
Angles it on middle, on a length. Kohli leans and flicks it wide of deep square leg. The fielder runs across and cuts it off. Two taken.
Another wayward delivery, on a length. Left alone.
This one shapes back in from way outside off. Kohli shoulders arms to it.
Just around the 4th stump line. Jadeja watchfully lets it through to the keeper.
A length ball, on off. Jadeja gets inside the line and blocks it out solidly.
This one shapes away off the deck, outside off. Jadeja leaves it alone.
Outside off, on a length. Jadeja watchfully lets it through.
Touch fuller, on off. Kohli takes a big stride forward and defends it to point for a quick single.
A length ball, outside off, hint of away shape. Kohli offers no shot.
On a length, on middle. Jadeja blocks it back to the bowler.
A length ball, on the pads, this is flicked to mid-wicket.
A length ball, on off. Jadeja blocks it on the off side.
A length ball, outside off. Left alone.
BEATEN! On a length, outside off. Jadeja looks to defend on the front foot but gets beaten on the outside edge.
A length ball, on off. Jadeja looks to defend but gets a thick outside edge through the gully region. The fielder does well to stop it near the ropes. Two runs taken.
Quick single! On middle, on a length. Jadeja hangs back and nudges it to short mid-wicket for a quick single.
Short of a length, around off. Jadeja sways away from it.
A length ball, slanting across, outside off. Jadeja looks to poke it but gets beaten on the outside edge.
On a length, on off. Jadeja blocks it to point.
Three runs taken! A full ball, on middle. Kohli flicks it through short mid-wicket. The fielder chases it back and stops it. Three runs taken.
Short in length, outside off. Kohli shoulders arms to it.
Who will bowl from the other end? James Anderson it is.
A touch fuller, on the pads. Jadeja tucks it to square leg.
A length ball, angling on the pads, this is flicked through square leg for a single.
Way outside off, on a length. Kohli lets it through to the keeper.
Slightly shorter, outside off. Kohli hops and taps it to point.
On a length, outside off. Kohli shoulders arms to it.
Serves a length ball, on off. Kohli prods forward to defend and does it off the inner half of his bat to square leg.

We are all set to begin Day 4! The England players stride out to the middle, followed by Virat Kohli and Ravindra Jadeja. Ollie Robinson to start with the ball. Remember, the play will be extended by 18 minutes today and a minimum of 95 overs will be bowled.

BREAKING NEWS! There is some news coming in that 4 of India's backroom staff, including Ravi Shastri are in isolation as they returned a positive Covid Test. However, the good news is that all the Indian and English players took their respective tests and none of those returned positive. Phew.

Pitch report - Dominic Cork says that it has turned into a belting batting track and it has dried up a little. Adds that it will be very interesting to see what Day 4 brings. States that if a heavy roller is used, then the pitch might become flatter.

Rohit Sharma is up for a chat. Rohit says that he was mentally prepared for the challenge and he knew that the management had faith in him. Adds that they always have to take risks and he was ready for it and it did not come to him as a surprise. States that he wanted to get big runs and he is pleased that he was able to play 250 balls. Adds that it was his goal to play as many balls as possible and spending time in the middle is the biggest takeaway.
Breaking news - KL Rahul has been fined 15 percent of his match fees as he showed dissent when he was given out caught behind on Day 3. A demerit point has also been added to his disciplinary record.

England, on the other hand, are in trouble. If they want to make a comeback in this game, they would need to pick up wickets as quickly as possible. They have already conceded a lead of 170 but they are not out of the game yet and if they can restrict India to as low a lead as possible, they can win from here. All-in-all, an exciting day awaits us.

How much will India aim for? That is the question in one's mind right now. Anything above 300 would be a very good score and India would want that. Kohli is looking in good touch and India would hope that he, along with the rest of the batters can stick around and take India past the 300 lead. The pitch looks good for batting and India would be disappointed with anything below 300.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 4 of the 4th Test between England and India. After a riveting Day 3, it is India who have moved ahead in the game as they lead by 171 runs and are looking good, despite losing two set batters late on Day 3. They have Kohli and Jadeja in the middle and they have plenty of batting left. England, on the other hand, are in need of wickets quickly before the lead swells up more. They have bowled well but with little reward. What will happen here?
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

Over and out! India will head into Day 4 with their noses in front. They are ahead by a good margin but with six sessions still left in this Test match, the tourists are not completely out of woods. England will have a fairly new ball to work with in the morning session and they would aim to create early inroads and restrict India's lead to as low as possible. Do join us on Sunday at 11 am local (10 am GMT) for all the action. The build-up will begin much in advance. Cheers!

England were mostly on the money but managed to pick only three wickets in the day's play. Missing out on a couple of opportunities to dismiss Rohit Sharma, in the first hour of the morning session, proved to be fatal. Not many would remember but Sharma offered a run out chance when he was on 28 but Anderson failed to score the direct hit from mid on. After that, there was one more chance to catch Rohit's edge but Rory Burns once again was the culprit. Rohit Sharma went on to score his maiden Test hundred outside home and made England pay heavily.

The first session was quite challenging for the batsmen but India braved that with minimum damage as they lost only KL Rahul. Day 3 is usually considered to be the best batting day at The Oval and as expected, the conditions were ripe for batting in the afternoon and the Indian pair of Rohit Sharma and Cheteshwar Pujara prospered. Their century stand pushed the hosts into a corner and they looked out of ideas. The pitch flattened out and the soft ball was not doing anything threatening.

From 99 down to 171 ahead. India have stormed back into this Test match. Apart from that one over with the second new ball when Ollie Robinson removed both Rohit Sharma and Cheteshwar Pujara in quick succession, the day belonged entirely to India. If Day 3 is the 'moving day', then this Test match has moved in favour of the visitors, at least for now.
Update 6 pm local (5 pm GMT) - The light, as expected, has not improved. The umpires have decided to call for STUMPS ON DAY 3.

Update 5.42 local (4.42 GMT) - The umpires are checking the light again! The crowd is booing and that means only one thing - PLAY STOPPED DUE TO BAD LIGHT. Joe Root wanted to bring Chris Woakes into the attack and the umpires had no other option but to stop the play. The players are leaving, it's not Stumps yet as we have another 18 minutes plus the extra 30 minutes to go. Hard to see light improving though. Stay tuned, we will keep you posted.
Flighted ball outside off, Jadeja gets forward and pushes it to covers again.
Tossed up on off, Jadeja watchfully defends it to the cover region.
Full on off, Jadeja defends it to covers.
Flatter ball on the pads, Jadeja looks to flick but it goes off the pads to fine leg. Two leg byes taken.
FOUR! Beautifully played! Shortish on the pads, Jadeja places it through the square leg region for a boundary.
Flatter ball outside off, Kohli punches it to point for one.
Moeen Ali to operate from the other end.
Full on middle, Jadeja looks to defend again but inside-edges it to the leg side. Bairstow appeals, thinking that it is pad first but the umpire turns it down.
Floated on middle, Jadeja looks to defend but gets an inside edge to short leg.
Looped up ball outside the off stump, Jadeja makes a leave to the keeper. Big spin on this one.
Tossed up on off, Jadeja defends it to covers.
Loopy ball outside off, Jadeja lets it go to the keeper.
Flatter ball outside off, Jadeja cuts it to point.

The two umpires get together. It has gone quite dark at the moment. The reserve umpire comes out and hands the light meter to one of the umpires. The reading is taken at both ends. They have decided to continue for now, maybe on the condition that England can bowl only spin. Joe Root has agreed and has brought himself into the attack. A bit strange decision. The second new ball is only 10 overs old, why would you want to get it softer? The only reason can be that there is a left-hander in the middle and his offies can trouble him.

FOUR! Kohli is oozing class at the moment! Anderson serves a half-volley, it's around off, once again Kohli leans forward and transfers his weight into the shot. Doesn't try to hit it hard, just times it through the gap at covers for a glorious boundary.
Hurls across a delivery in the channel outside off, Kohli finds it to be too wide and makes a leave.
Aims the off stump with a length ball, Kohli gets forward and defends it to the off side. Gentle hands.
On a length and outside off, some extra bounce, Kohli shoulders arms.
FOUR! Elegance! Anderson bowls it full and around off, Kohli leans forward and unveils a lovely square drive for a boundary. The lead is now 160 runs.
Slightly short and on off, Virat stays back and once again allows the ball to come to him. He then plays it late and taps it down to backward point.
Hits the deck hard and lands it on a good length around off, Jadeja is solidly behind the line in defense.
On a good length around middle, Jadeja closes the face of his bat and helps it to mid-wicket.
Fullish and on off, Jadeja draws forward and defends it from the inner half of his blade.
Full in length on middle and leg, served from wide of the crease, Kohli fails to flick and it goes off his pads to fine leg. The bowler appeals and the batters cross. Given as a leg bye.
Angling in from a length around off, Kohli lets it come to him and then blocks it on the leg side.
A touch short and outside off, Kohli stands across in his crease to guard his stumps as he makes a leave.
The batsman lets the ball go outside his off stump. A pretty harmless over from Jimmy.
On a length, around middle and off, Jadeja defends it back to the bowler.
In the channel outside off, Jadeja makes an easy leave.
Back of a length, around off, Jadeja stands tall and plays it down to cover-point.
Beats the outside edge! Anderson takes a length ball away from the left-hander, the angle does Jadeja in, as he feels for it and misses.
On a good length, outside off and angling away, Jadeja allows it through to the keeper.

Drinks! What a passage of play we have had here! Rohit Sharma and Cheteshwar Pujara started the session well but then the second new ball changed things as Ollie Robinson sent both Sharma and Pujara packing in the same over. Kohli and Jadeja have held the fort since then and they need to continue. England would look to pick some more wickets before Stumps. An exciting final passage of play coming up.
FOUR! Class of Virat Kohli. Robinson pitches it up and around off, Virat Kohli leans into the drive and crunches it through the gap at covers. India lead by 155 runs.

Howzzat? Robinson goes wide of the crease and angles it in on a length around middle, Kohli tries to flick but misses. He is hit high on the pads, they appeal but the umpire shakes his head. Too high. England have only one review left, so Root is also being careful here.

FOUR! Nicely played! Robinson delivers it on a length close to off, Kohli plays late and opens the face of his bat to guide it past the slip cordon. Rory Burns gives the chase from second slip, puts in a slide near the fence and pulls it back. The umpire gets it checked upstairs and the replays show that his left knee touched the cushion when he was in contact with the ball.
A touch short and around off, Virat shoulders arms.
Full and on off, Kohli gets forward and pushes it with an angled bat to point.
In the right channel outside off, the batsman shoulders arms to let that one through.
On a length around off, defended from the crease to covers.

Appeal for a caught behind! The finger stays down. There was some noise. On a length around middle and off, Jadeja looks to defend but misses. It sneaks past him to the keeper and Bairstow appeals after collecting the ball. Maybe it kissed the flap of the front pad. Root opts not to take the review as Anderson was unsure.
Identical to the last delivery, again Jadeja makes a watchful leave.
Brilliant line from Anderson. He angles it away from the southpaw, on a length, Jadeja stays back to cover his stumps and offers no shot.
Back of a length around leg, Jadeja tries to glance but misses and is hit on the thigh pad.

Full and around off, Kohli looks to defend but it takes the inner edge and rolls behind square leg for a single. The throw comes to the keeper who gets a bad bounce and fails to collect. Kohli looks for the second run but then decides against it.
fuller and on off, Jadeja offers a straight bat as he defends it back. Two maidens in a row.
Pitches it up and around off, Jadeja gets forward and pushes it defensively to mid off.
Fuller and on middle, Jadeja tries to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Keeps it close to off, on a length, Jadeja gets half-forward and defends it to the off side.
Fuller and closer to off, Jadeja gets behind the line and pushes it back to the bowler.
Delivers it on a length around middle and off, Jadeja stays back and defends it to cover-point.
Anderson bends his back and digs it short around off, Kohli gets on top of the bounce and plays it down to point.
In the channel outside off, an easy leave for the Indian skipper.
On and around off, a length ball, Kohli plays late and taps it down to point.
Fullish and on off, Kohli uses his wrists and pushes it down to mid on.
Anderson gets closer to the off stump line, serves it full, an outswinger, Virat defends it back to the bowler.
Back of a length, outside off, Kohli has nothing to do with it.
FOUR! Streaky! Fuller in length, outside off and angling away, Jadeja looks to drive through the line but edges it wide of backward point for a boundary.
On a length around off, Kohli presses forward with an angled bat and eases it down to third man. Haseeb Hameed chases it down and the batters collect three.
Too full and on off, Kohli leans forward and across before flicking it to mid on.
Fuller and on off, angling in, Kohli pushes it to cover-point.
In the region outside off, on a length, Kohli allows it through.
On and around off, angling away, Jadeja pushes it defensively towards point for a brisk run.
Pitches it up and around off, Kohli pushes it with gentle hands to mid off.
Extra bounce on this one, on a length and outside off, Kohli leaves and it thuds on his back thigh. Big movement.
In the zone outside off, Kohli shoulders arms.
Fuller and on off, Kohli gets forward, opens the face of the bat slightly and defends it to covers.
Appeal for a caught behind! Back of a length, outside off and holding its line, some extra bounce too, Kohli pushes inside the line and misses.
On a length around off, defended to covers.
Who will walk out now? Ravindra Jadeja it is and James Anderson returns into the attack.

OUT! The new ball has brought two breakthroughs for England and Ollie Robinson is flying in celebration. Ollie delivers it on a shortish length and gets it to jag back in sharply. Pujara is caught on the back foot as he tries to defend by going on his toes. There seems to be an inside edge and the ball deflects off the back thigh pad to third slip. Moeen Ali collects the ball and the hosts appeal vociferously. The umpire remains still. England are very sure and take the DRS. The UltraEdge detects a spike and India have lost their third wicket. The momentum is shifting in this Test match again with both the set batsmen dismissed in no time.
Commentary.Howout: c Moeen Ali b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Review time! England are very confident that they have got Cheteshwar Pujara as well and they have gone for the review. There is a spike as the ball passed the bat and England have another.
Virat is off the mark in a tricky manner. An in-dipper from Robinson, on a length close to off, Kohli tries to defend but it takes the inner edge and runs down to fine leg for a run.
Full and around middle, angling in, Kohli closes the face of his bat and pushes it to mid-wicket.
In the channel outside off, on a length, Kohli allows it through to the keeper.
Delivers it on a length and angles it down the leg side, Kohli tries to flick but misses. Jonny Bairstow collects and appeals but nothing from the umpire.
Virat Kohli makes his way out to the middle.

OUT! Rohit holes out, once again while attempting a pull shot. Ollie Robinson delivers it short and around off, it has not bounced much and has come off the surface slowly. Rohit aims for the pull shot but is way too early into the shot. The ball kisses the top edge and flies to fine leg. Chris Woakes moves across to his left and makes no mistake in the deep. England have a wicket out of nowhere. Sharma would be devastated with this tame dismissal. End of a century stand and a magnificent knock by the Hitman. A wicket immediately with the second new ball and the hosts have an opening. Can they capitalize? The lead is 137 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Chris Woakes b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: The second new ball is available now. Will it be taken immediately? Yes, it has been taken. Ollie Robinson is into the attack.
Quicker one, flatter and wider outside off, Pujara allows it through. England have finished the last few overs in the blink of an eye.
Flatter and shorter on middle, Pujara immediately goes back and tucks it to deep square leg for a couple.
Loopy and full around off, Pujara skips down the track and works it wide of mid-wicket. Screams 'wait' as the fielder from the deep is charging towards the ball.

Walks down the pitch to a full ball and flicks it to mid-wicket.
Spinning in from around off, Sharma moves back, allows it to come to him and then nurdles it to square leg for a single.
Tossed up and around off, Pujara defends it from the front foot to the leg side.
Floated one, full and around middle, it's driven through covers for a run. The 150-run stand comes up.

Wayward delivery, full and down the leg side, further spinning away, Sharma leaves and Bairstow stretches to his left to collect it.

Loopy and full around off, Pujara leans forward and wrists it towards mid-wicket.
Flatter and on off,Pujara gets back and defends it back to the bowler.
Tossed up, around off and spinning in, Rohit goes back and nudges it to the right side of the square leg umpire for a single.
Flighted and full outside off, this time it has been pushed to covers.
Loopy and full around off, Rohit lunges and defends it with his bat and pad together. This one spun a bit.
Fullish and around leg, Pujara hurries down the track and flicks it to mid-wicket.
Fuller and on middle, Rohit lifts his back leg a bit as he flicks it through the gap at mid-wicket for a run.
Tossed up on middle, Sharma leans a bit and helps it with gentle hands to square leg.
Fullish and on middle, flicked on the leg side but straight to square leg again.
Quicker and fuller on leg, defended on the leg side.
Floated one, full and around leg, Sharma works it off his pads to square leg.
Too full and on off, Rohit gets forward and knocks it down to long on for an easy run. India lead by 123.
Floated one, wide outside off and spinning in a bit, Sharma makes a leave.
Presses forward to a full ball and defends it to the off side.
Short again, outside off, Rohit delays his shot and places his cut shot wide of backward point. Picks up a couple. Elegant.
A little short and outside off, turning in, Pujara goes back and cuts it to deep cover for a run.
Shortish and outside off, Rohit moves back and punches it to long on for a single.

Quicker and flatter, on the pads, Pujara clips it across the line but again the square leg fielder is there to stop a run.

Loopy delivery, full and around off, Pujara defends it back.
Shortish and on middle, Rohit goes back and works it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Joe Root comes on now.
Flatter one, on the pads, helped to square leg.
Pujara is not holding back. Short around leg, he pulls but finds Root at backward square leg.

This is smart batting! Sharma anticipates the line to be around leg and hence steps back to make room. He then strokes it wide of mid off and it races away. Overton himself gives the chase and puts in a slide near the fence to pull it back. Saves one run. Full marks to Craig's commitment.

Shortish and around off, Pujara plays it with the angle and places it to the right of the gully fielder for a single.
On middle and leg, worked on the leg side but straight to the fielder at square leg.

Appeal for a caught behind! Nothing from the umpire. Overton goes short and around leg, Pujara tries to pull but misses. It goes closely past his gloves to the keeper. Jonny Bairstow collects and looks to jump first in appeal. He then holds himself back and appeals. Overton is not interested in appealing at all. No gloves, the UltraEdge also confirms.

Presses forward to a full ball on off and works it off his pads to the leg side. Easy going for India at the moment with nothing much happening from the pitch. This stand has moved to 129 runs and India lead by 113.
Fuller this time, around off, Rohit drives off the front foot to mid off.

Slightly short and around off, not much pace there, Rohit moves back and glances it through square leg for a couple of runs.
Serves it on a length and around off, Rohit stays on the back foot and punches it down to mid off.
Overton continues to bowl short and around middle, Pujara pulls it this time but finds Root at backward square leg.
Fractionally short again, on middle, Pujara sits back and plays it down with soft hands to mid-wicket.
A touch short and on middle, Pujara moves back and works it towards the fielder on the leg side, this time in front of square leg.
Shortish and around leg, tickled on the leg side but straight to the fielder at backward square leg.

FOUR! Fifty for Cheteshwar Pujara! Back of a length, around off and angling away, Pujara sticks on the back foot and just uses the pace of the bowler to guide it behind backward point for a boundary. Found some form in Leeds and has just extended it here at The Oval. Can Pujara end his drought and find a century this time?
Overton bangs it in short, from 'round the wicket, Pujara ducks and evades it easily.
On a good length and around off, Rohit plays it late from the crease and guides it towards backward point.
Fuller and on off, a good off drive from Rohit but it's not in the gap. The Hitman is looking at ease.
A touch short and on off, Sharma stays back and uses the angle of the bowler to help it towards mid-wicket.
Keeps his line around off and operates on a fuller length, Sharma is forward as he pushes it down to mid off.
This one is very full and on off, Rohit drives it back and Woakes collects it to his left.
Starts with a delivery angling in around off, Sharma gets behind the line and pushes it back to the bowler.
Who will bowl from the other end? Chris Woakes it is.

Right then! Post Tea, India would look to carry on batting as long as they can and get a big lead while England would want to break this partnership first and then make further inroads into the Indian batting line-up. This game has turned in the favour of India but things can change quickly in cricket. What will happen? Do join us at 3 pm GMT (4 pm local) for all the action after Tea.

England, on the other hand, had to toil hard after Lunch! James Anderson and Chris Woakes bowled well and had the Indian batters in trouble on a few occasions but they were not rewarded. Moeen Ali has looked unthreatening so far and the Indian batters have made merry off his bowling. Ollie Robinson looked tired while Craig Overton did not bowl much. They have a big task in hand going into the final session of the day.

Starting after Lunch, India got off to a positive start as Pujara looked really good. He played those cut shots really well and looked in sublime touch. Rohit Sharma started off slowly but then took the attack to Moeen Ali and reached his century, his first away from home. India now lead by 100 runs and they still have 9 wickets in hand. They look on top at the moment but they have to remain focused and carry on batting.

The good work done in the first session is a thing of the past now and they will have to switch on and start afresh. Do join us at 12.40 pm GMT (1.40 pm local) for all the action after Lunch.

India are effectively 9 for 1 at this stage and this Test match continues to hang right in the balance. Rohit Sharma is approaching his fifty and after surviving three nervy moments, he would be aiming for a big knock. His partner Cheteshwar Pujara has looked very positive in his 21-ball stay so far and his strike rate of 66.7 hints that he is looking for runs.

End of an absorbing session and India will be quite pleased with their efforts. The conditions were challenging for the batsmen but Rohit Sharma and KL Rahul braved everything together for most parts. England worked hard with the ball but their lengths were not accurate enough. They had mastered their lengths in Headingley by bowling a bit fuller but here they appeared more on the shorter side. A couple of chances also went begging in the first hour when Rohit's run out chance was missed and then Rory Burns offered Sharma yet another life. Jimmy eventually managed to eke out an edge off KL Rahul's bat and that was the only success for the Three Lions in the morning session.

Did you know? On this day, exactly 42 years ago, Sunil Gavaskar notched up 221 runs in the 4th innings at The Oval. It was a breathtaking knock and the original Little Master almost helped India achieve a miracle win, chasing a mammoth target of 438. That game was eventually drawn with India remaining a few runs short. To date, Gavaskar's knock remains the highest score by an Indian in the fourth innings. Truly inspirational.

Ravi Shastri had mentioned recently that all the pressure is on England as this is their home Test series and India have done what they had to do when England visited them earlier this year. The Indian coach smartly played down the situation but we all know there's a burning desire for India to win a Test series in England. Day 3 of the 4th Test can drop us a hint of whether it's achievable or not.

Shardul Thakur with the bat, Umesh Yadav with the ball, Ollie Pope's knock and Chris Woakes' all-round quality - It's safe to say that this Test match belongs to the non-regulars. They've had a big impact already after two innings and let's wait and watch if the regulars get their act together for the next three days. It's always said that the Dukes ball starts to swing more after 12-15 overs in England, so a big challenge awaits India and along with that you cannot discount the early morning conditions. After what happened at Headingley, the tourists will be extra careful and seeing off Anderson and co. in the first session would be the key.

Two days, 20 wickets and some rearguard batting - That's been the story of The Oval Test thus far. We're a firm believer in momentum but currently, as we head into the 'moving day', it's hard to guess which team has it. This is what happens when two top-class teams collide who have similar strengths and weaknesses. Just because England still have a lead, we can't hand the advantage to them as the Indian openers almost halved the deficit after batting bravely in the last evening session. So, let's sit on the fence and for the moment use that cliched line - This Test is tantalizingly poised and the morning session of Day 3 holds great importance. Right then, on that note, allow us to welcome you for the coverage and stay tuned as we head towards the action.

The openers batted solidly! Indian openers had their task cut out. They showed a lot of discipline and also scored runs at a brisk pace. Rohit Sharma is the Man of the Match. He says that he wanted to be on the field as much as he could and that this hundred was a special one. He adds that after being down and out in the first innings and then going on to post 466 was an amazing collective batting effort. He says that it's his first away hundred and it's his best one yet and commends all the other players. He says that the bowlers did the job and the whole team is pumped right now. Also adds that he doesn't care much about big scores and is happy to score runs as required by his team. He also adds that batting in these conditions, specially at the top of the order is not easy and recollects the training at Durham. He says that the training helped them a lot after the WTC final and the results could be seen in this series. He ends by saying that he feels fit and it's just about what the physio says.

The Indian skipper, Virat Kohli says that he thinks the best thing about both the wins was how the team showed character. Mentions that they put up a good total on the board and it was going to be tough to chase. Adds that the bowlers were exceptional and it would rate this performance amongst his top 3. Tells that the bowlers exploited reverse-swing conditions perfectly today and they believed as a team that they could get 10 wickets today. Mentions that Bumrah was just outstanding. Informs that to give away 27 runs from 22 overs speaks volumes. Goes onto say that if England will give a chance to them, India will take it with both hands. Credits Shardul Thakur and says that his first innings made the difference and his fifty in the second innings was noteworthy as well. States that they focus on their job and do not look over stats and don't bother with the noise that comes from outside and they try to perform as a group. Tells that this win gives the team more motivation to go out and win the final Test as well. Says that the fans have been amazing as well.

The England skipper, Joe Root says, that when they came out to bat today, the match was there for the taking but they couldn't capitalize on the start. He then credits the opposition bowlers and mentions that they showed real skill. He also goes on to say that the bowling was world-class and they will want to improve on how to counter it. He adds that there will be swing at Old Trafford as well. He mentions that they need to be more ruthless and clinical and is disappointed with how the lead was turned against them. Mentions that they need big partnerships and not settle for starts and collectively need to put in a better batting performance. About the slip catching, he says that the players do practice a lot and it's just about being brave and taking the chances. He also adds that yes, they have had injuries but that cannot be an excuse and they need one big push in the final Test to level the series.

England were in the ascendancy in the first innings. They had a nice lead of 99 runs but that's all it was. The lead was soon turned to dust and the hosts were out of sorts with the ball in the second innings. They did not get any movement and the visitors took advantage of a flat pitch. 368 runs still looked a good score to chase on a flat pitch and England started off well. The openers negated Day 4 and then continued to merry their way to put a 100-run stand. It was still fine when Malan got out but after that they had a collapse and lost four wickets for just six runs. Root tried to hold fort but there's only so much one man can do. Wickets kept tumbling and Root also departed. England crumbled under pressure and weren't able to show much resistance. They went on to suffer a heavy defeat in the end.

What a turnaround it has been from India. Who would have thought that after being bowled for 191 runs in the first innings, the visitors would go on to win by 157 runs? The batters, Rohit Sharma in particular destroyed the English attack in the second innings but was very well supported by Pant, Thakur and some handy contributions from the tail, which put India in the driving seat. The bowlers toiled hard late on Day 4 but couldn't get a single breakthrough. That however, changed on Day 5 and Shardul Thakur provided an early wicket to set the tone for the rest of the day. From then on, Bumrah and Jadeja were brilliant and after Lunch, they made short work of the hosts and all together the visitors picked up six wickets in that session. Umesh Yadav had a brilliant burst in the end with the second new ball to clean up the England tail.
What a victory this has been for India. Incredible scenes all around the stadium. Virat Kohli is pumped up, India are pumped up.

India have won the fourth Test by 157 runs and have taken a crucial 2-1 lead heading into the final Test. Incredible scenes all around the stadium. This cracker of a series just keeps swinging like a pendulum.

What a sensational phase of play for India. Jadeja started well and got Hameed very early after the break off the rough. Bumrah then showed his class and dismantled Bairstow and Pope and got to his 100th Test wicket in the process. Jadeja removed Ali as well for a duck and then Shardul Thakur again got the breakthrough removing the dangerous Joe Root. India are now just two wickets away and have as many as 37.5 overs to get that. Join us 4.00 pm local ( 3 pm GMT) for the final session.

England started the session with intent, Root reverse-sweeping off the first ball of the session for four but all that changed pretty quickly as Hameed was the first one to depart. England then fell like a pack of cards as they lost Bairstow, Pope and Ali pretty quickly. Only Root managed to stay solid and England would have banked on him to stay for long but that didn't happen as well. England need another 175 runs but that is way out of their reach and only have 2 wickets in the tank.

India bossed this session completely! The bowlers managed to scalp six wickets to put England on the back foot and are on the verge of a victory. England will have their heads down and will be pretty disappointed with how they played post Lunch.

The Indian bowlers couldn't extract much from the pitch but didn't allow English openers to score singles too easily. They bowled a lot fuller and straighter but the batters did well to combat that. It was then Shardul Thakur, who scalped the first wicket in his first over itself to make early inroads. India had Malan too later and could have had Hameed earlier but was put down by Siraj on 55. India need 8 wickets and England need 237 more. It won't be easy particularly with Ravindra Jadeja bowling in that rough patch but the pitch is still good to bat on and England would love to take it to their advantage. What will happen? Join us for the second session at 1.40 pm local (12.40 GMT) to find out.

Rory Burns and Haseeb Hameed were pretty solid at the start. Burns brought up his half century as well but got out right away after that. Hameed continued to stay solid as he went past his fifty while Malan did well to hang around despite Jadeja causing some problems to the left-hander but lost his wicket in a run out as there was a mix-up between him and Hameed. England would now hope that Joe Root and Haseeb Hameed continue to bat as long as they can.

Gary Pratt, Gary Pratt, howzzat? This is for all cricketing fans. How many of you remember Gary Pratt? He never played a game for England but is remembered fondly by many fans of the Ashes and England. Of course, bitterly by Australia as well. The then Aussie captain, Ricky Ponting, had raised the usage of substitutes on the cricketing field and got angered and irritated when Pratt fired a throw from cover to catch Ponting short at the bowler's end, during the 2005 Ashes. Something similar could have happened here. Full, around off, Rory Burns came forward and then went back to play it to the leg side. Now, as is the flow of momentum, Burns went out of the crease and at that very moment, Suryakumar Yadav, the substitute, standing at short leg, stopped the ball to his left. He immediately transferred the ball to his right hand and fired a throw at the striker's end. He missed and every Indian player on the field had his hands over his head. Was Burns caught napping? He does get two overthrows as the ball goes to fine leg. No sir. Replays show that even if Yadav had hit the stumps, Burns would have been home. Surya reacted swiftly but so did Burns as he did not commit the cardinal sin of committing way too much into the run. So he was able to stop and turn back and get his bat back in the crease, before the ball could hit the stumps. Fantastic cricket at the end of the day, giving us more drama!

He asked Pant, Suryakumar Yadav, Rahane and even Rahul. None of them looked even remotely confident and Surya even shook his head. 'AAGE AAKE KHELA WOH?' asked Kohli. Meaning, 'Did he lunge and play?' Kohli was seemingly indicating that because of that lunge, the ball might have hit him low on the pads. Contrary to everyone's suggestions, Kohli went for the review, purely on his gut instinct. However, Ball Tracker showed the ball to be going over the leg stump. Cannot blame Kohli totally here, one could imagine that lunge from Hameed might have tempted him to think that the ball will hit the wickets. Review lost by India.
